column4: Both papers are categorized under “Evaluation Research” and make use of a technical experiment as their evaluation method. In other words, the “Model‐Based Analysis of Microservice Resiliency Patterns” and “Supporting Architectural Decision Making on Data Management in Microservice Architectures” papers both employ technical experiments—a systematic, controlled setup where input data and tool support (even if not openly available) are used to investigate their respective research contributions.

column4: Based on the provided evidence, the usability of objects in papers co‐authored by Lu Xiao has not been evaluated using a single, stand‐alone “usability method.” Instead, the evaluation is embedded in a broader framework where the evaluation targets (captured under “Classifications_1”) are characterized by quality properties. In particular, evaluation sub-properties—including usability—and related quality aspects (e.g. aspects under “Quality of Method” such as accuracy, effectiveness, and functional suitability) are used to assess the objects. That is, the papers apply a quality‐oriented, criteria‐based evaluation approach where usability is one of the measured sub-properties.

column4: Based on the evidence, research objects evaluated using Grounded Theory appear in two distinct publication periods. Specifically, one cluster is associated with research published in 2019 (for example, the study on industrial control systems’ architectural security weaknesses) and another with research published in 2021 (for example, the study on quantum computing platforms). This indicates that when the evaluation method “Grounded Theory” is applied (as seen in multiple KG paths via ‘Classifications_1’), research objects are distributed between these two years.

column4:
Based on the provided context, the publications evaluated using the Argumentation evaluation method (via Classifications_1) and having a research object of “Reference Architecture” are distributed across the three publication years as follows:
• 2019 – e.g., “Flaws in Flows: Unveiling Design Flaws via Information Flow Analysis”
• 2020 – e.g., “A Flexible Architecture for Key Performance Indicators Assessment in Smart Cities”
• 2021 – e.g., “System- and Software-level Architecting Harmonization Practices for Systems-of-Systems: An exploratory case study on a long‐running large‐scale scientific instrument.”
In short, one research object instance is identified in each of the publication years 2019, 2020, and 2021.

column98: Which papers have Ingo Weber as an author and apply the evaluation method Argumentation? Rank the papers in descending order of their publication year.

A second paper – “A Flexible Architecture for Key Performance Indicators Assessment in Smart Cities” – is published in 2020. Together these indicate that, among the investigated papers for that period, one is from 2018 and one is from 2020.

column99: The distribution of papers with the evaluation method Argumentation between 2019 and 2021 is as follows: In 2019 two papers were published and in 2020 three papers were published. However, in 2021 no paper was published with the evaluation method Argumentation.
